@node Introduction "What the hell is it?"

 @{b}@{u}What the hell is it?@{uu}@{ub}

The  program  calculates and displays electrical/gravitional
potential  distribution of charged particles/masses. It is a
potential  distribution  NOT  field  distribution. Computing
field  distribution  takes  much longer (need to calculate a
vector sum) and the output picture is similar.

The  program  generates pictures in 256 greyscale. The color
of  points  is computed according to the value of potential.
There  is  no 'save IFF' option -- use a screen grabber, but
be warned - some of them doesn't do it rite with 256 colored
screens!   After  saving  load  picture  in  your  favourite
painting  program  and  set  palette  ranges  in your way. I
include source code so you can improve it.

The program have no GUI and it has to be run from CLI/Shell.
But  you  can  use this fact and write a batch file (script)
that  will  generate  pictures  for you. You can for example
make  some  animations  this  way  but  you  need to compute
parameters. It's not convinient but it's completely free!

If  you  want to see equipotential lines you simply load the
picture  into  any  better  painting  program (e.g. Personal
Paint)  and  simply  set  numbers  of  colors to 16 in image
format. This will show 'pseudo' equipotential lines.

In  this  archive you can find some executables, source code
and example pictures.

@{b}Future@{ub}:

I doubt it, but...

@endnode

@node Requirements "Will it run on my Amy?"

 @{b}@{u}Will it run on my Amy?@{uu}@{ub}

You need Kickstart 3.0+ and AGA Chipset.

The  program  computes  pictures  in  up  to 256 colors so I
needed  AGA.

In  drawer  you  can find a few versions for different
processors and FPUs. Generally:

-  program  with plain filename will run on ANY procesor and
   no FPU is needed,

-  program  which  filename  contains  processor  number  is
   optimized just for this processor,

-  program  which  filename  contains  'FP'  requires a math
   coprocessor

The  program  was  created  and tested on A1200 / HD / 6MB /
68882 / VGA.

If you want different version of compiled program let @{"me"
link Author} know.

@endnode

@node Installation "How to install?"

 @{b}@{u}How to install?@{uu}@{ub}

Just copy main drawer "Graviton" where you like. The program
must  be  run  from  CLI  or  Shell  and  must be given some
@{"arguments" link Usage}.

@endnode

@node Usage "How to use it?"

 @{b}@{u}How to use it?@{uu}@{ub}

Program needs 3 arguments - N, BRIGHTNESS and SEED. Usage:

                  electron N BRIGHTNESS SEED

N          - number of particles,

BRIGHTNESS - Brightness of the picture. The bigger it is the
             brighter  the  picture becomes. You need to set
             it  experimentally.  But  be  carefull - if the
             value  is  too  small  the  picture will be too
             dark, if too big the picture will be too bright
             (even white).

SEED       - The  seed  value  for  srand() function. If you
             have  a  battery clock in your Amy use value of
             -1. This will automaticly generate a seed value
             based  on  current  time.  If  you don't have a
             clock  use  any  positive  value  for different
             pictures.


@{b}@{u}IMPORTAINT!!!@{uu}@{ub}

To halt program during generating picture move mouse pointer
to  top  left corner of screen and wait till current line is
drawn.  The  same  when  program  finishes. Sorry for such a
stupid thing, but it was the easiest. I'm so lazy...

See some @{"examples" link Examples}.

@endnode

@node Examples "Quick start"

 @{b}@{u}Quick start@{uu}@{ub}

Here are some interesting parameters. Try them out!

electron 200 1 -1
electron 10 10 123
electron 20 3 1363

@endnode

